crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects Tiny Shell - an open-source UNIX backdoor
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Mandiant

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB pie executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, BuildID[sha1]=768b19a38f685c3601ac14c269db046e955ef757, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a sophisticated remote access trojan (RAT) or backdoor featuring reverse shell and file management capabilities. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) Interactive remote shell execution via sub_4066b8, which uses openpty and ioctl to allocate a TTY, disables command history by setting 'HISTFILE=', and executes '/bin/sh'; 2) Flexible C2 connectivity in main(), supporting both a bind shell (listening) and a reverse shell (connecting back to a host provided via -c); 3) File exfiltration and delivery via sub_406569 (read) and sub_40660c (create/write); 4) Implementation of a custom encrypted protocol (evidenced by complex bitwise logic and S-box tables in sub_401e40 and sub_40306f) to obfuscate command-and-control traffic.
